<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN RANKS 29TH TOURISM ECONOMY: WTTC
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei, April 19 (CNA) 04/19/07  20:08:07 (By Ruth Wang)
</P>
<P>
Taiwan has been ranked the world's 29th largest "tourism
economy," with its tourism industry contributing 4.52 percent of
its total gross domestic product (GDP) for 2006, an official of
the Council for Economic Planning and Development (CEPD) said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting statistics compiled by the World Travel and Tourism
Council (WTCC), the official said that Taiwan had over 3.52
million foreign visitors in 2006, 151,207 of whom came only for
sightseeing, an increase of 9.3 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Tourists spent US$34.43 billion in 2006, a rise of 5.75 percent
year-on-year, higher than the global average of 4.85 percent. Of
this amount, direct consumption in transportation, housing and
shopping accounted for US$4.19 billion, representing 1.18 percent
of the total GDP, according to the statistics, the official said,
adding that the amount has helped to create 170,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
The official said the tourism industry's  good performance
indicates that the government's marketing strategy has worked and
he added that the CEPD is confident Taiwan tourism will achieve a
better ranking in the future.
</P>
